Days after the retest, an exhausted Yui returns to the club room with perfect marks. To celebrate, the girls ask Yui to play the guitar chords she had learned, only to find that Yui has completely forgotten them.

Azusa officially joins the club, but is shocked to find everyone drinking tea and eating cake instead of practicing. She yells at them when Sawako tells her off for actually practicing, but Yui manages to calm her down with a surprising tactic. Despite her objections, Azusa finds herself weak against Tsumugi's tea and cakes. Yui herself is rather shocked that Azusa plays guitar much better than herself. Sawako brings a pair of cat ears for Azusa to wear, much to Azusa's discomfort, leading Yui to give her the nickname "Azu-nyan", as "nyan" is the Japanese counterpart of "meow". Noticing that Azusa is a bit upset, Mio encourages the band to practice more, but the group quickly reverts to its lazy state. Azusa then becomes frustrated, wondering as to why the band members she admired at the live performance behave as they do. After Azusa expresses her frustration, Mio explains to her that she stays in the band because they have fun performing together and because they like each other, thus convincing Azusa to stay.

table-0520-930.pgTitle: Oil Campaign chronology of World War II
table-0520-930.caption: Chronology
data: Oil and other installations in Ruhr
24 Wellington, 24 Whitleys, and 12 Hampdens attacked oil refineries and railways in Germany and troops in Belgium.
Hampdens attacked oil refineries near Hamburg.
The Bremen oil refinery was bombed.
24 Whitleys and 6 Hampdens bombed "oil and communication targets in Germany".
The Future Strategy report predicted "Germany's oil stocks might be exhausted--and Germany's situation disastrous--by June 1941." :4
43 Wellingtons bombed an oil depot near Antwerp. A Redeventza refinery was at Antwerp.
Less than half of 135 aircraft dispatched bombed the Gelsenkirchen synthetic oil plants.
222 aircraft (the highest number to one target) conducted the first "oil plant directive" mission on 17 oil production targets.
To enable bombing of "Roumanian oil installations", a British Expeditionary Force established a 'Balkan front'. :160
The Kolnische Gummifaden Fabrik tire and tube factory at Deutz on the east bank of the Rhine was entirely destroyed. :215
The "Bombers' Baedeker" identified oil, communications, and ball bearings were "bottleneck" German industries.
The Soviet Union's VVS bombed the oil installations.
The US "Enemy Oil Committee" was established as a counterpart to the British "Technical Sub-Committee on Axis Oil" (Hartley Committee).
The Axis Oil Position in Europe, November 1942 estimated that Romanian oil fields contribute 33% of Axis supplies. :41
The German Strategy in 1943 predicted Nazi Germany will have increased domestic oil supplies in mid-1943. :42

The COA's comprehensive plan identified the strategic bombing objective was to "bring about a high degree of destruction in a few really essential industries than to dissipate bombing efforts over a large number of targets [in] many industries." 19 vital industries were identified: Petroleum was 3rd (39 targets), "Synthetic rubber and rubber tires" were 6th (12 targets) and "Coking plants" were 10th (89 targets). In particular, destruction of 13 hydrogenation plants and 12 Ploesti refineries would reduce "German petroleum resources" by 90%.:6
183 B-17's are dispatched to synthetic oil installations at Bochum, Gelsenkirchen and Recklinghausen
The 384 BG bombed the Gelsenkirchen "oil refinery".
Mission 121: 229 of 323 B-17s bombed 495 tons:164 on the marshalling yard and oil plants.

96 of 328 B-17s bombed 238 tons on the "Hydrier Werke Scholven A.G." (damaged) and the Gelsenkirchener Bergwerke (missed). Gelsenkirchener Bergwerke plants were also at Duisburg-Hamborn (BRUCKHAUSEN Benzol Plant) and Dortmund. A Gelsenkirchen target was also attacked on November 19,:163 and Gelsenkirchen Mission 134 on November 19 was rerouted to bomb the German-Dutch border due to malfunctioning blind-bombing PFF equipment in bad weather.

"losses of oil stocks … caused by Allied attacks during the first eight months of 1943 [were] 400,000 tons. … Approximately 75 per cent of Roumanian crude is a waxy, viscous oil which becomes solid at temperatures below 69" degrees (J.I.C (43) 480).

1,000 tons of bombs dropped on Ludwigshafen, :337 and the 447 BG bombed the Ludwigshafen oil refinery. In addition to the nearby Oppau plants, Ludwigshafen targets included a small synthetic oil plant and an oil refinery that used the dehydrogenation process to improve "gasoline quality". Dr. Wurster of the Ludwigshafen Military Government was the "managing director of Oppau and Ludwigshafen." Ludwigshafen targets were subsequently bombed by the 8AF on March 2, March 31, and May 27.

The 317 BS bombed the oil refinery. Circa January 1944, the Enemy Oil Committee identified that Italian refining had ceased in August 1943. Italian refineries were at Fiume (Ramsa plant), La Spezia, Leghorn, Trieste (Aquila & SIAF plants), and Venice.
Budapest, Sofia, Bucharest, and Vienna were identified as second priority objectives for 15AF "area attack".
[Plan_for_Completion_of_Combined_Bomber_Offensive|Plan for Completion of Combined Bomber Offensive]
34 B-24s of the 450 BG targeted the marshalling yards and bombed the "Vega Oil Refinery".
By May 1944, only 1.1% of Allied bombs had been used on oil targets. :4
The marshalling yards and oil refineries were bombed.
12 Bostons achieved near misses at an oil depot at Bruges.
Mission 376: 38 B-17s bombed an oil target at Ruhland/Schwarz-Heide.
The 447 BG bombed the oil refinery.

32 B-24s of the 450 BG attacked the "Româno-Americană Oil Refinery", but failed due to the smoke screens. :153 The 450 BG also bombed the Româno-Americană refinery on June 6, 24, & July 15; and the Concordia Vega refinery on July 9, 22
Spaatz ordered that "the primary aim of the Eighth and Fifteenth Air Forces would be to deny oil to the enemy". :118
36 P-38s dive-bombed 3 Ploieşti oil refineries by flying under the smoke screens. :153
B-24s bombed an oil installation at Constanţa.
The 461 BG bombed the Giurgiu oil storage. 80 miles southeast of Ploieşti, Giurgiu was "the most important transshipment point in Europe".:8
The 461 BG targeted the Porto Marghera oil storage and hit the aluminum plant.
Mission 412: 61 B-24s hit the Emmerich, Germany oil refinery. Deutsche Gasolin plants were at Emmerich, Dollbergen, and Korneuburg.
B-24s bombed an oil target at Pardubice.
39 B-24s of the 450 BG targeted the oil refinery.
3 bombs from 35 Mosquitoes fell into the plant area, and 3 civilians were killed outside the factory—a farmer, a lorry-driver, and a housewife.
B-24s bombed the Lobau oil refinery west of Vienna.
B-24s bombed the oil refinery at Schwechat in Vienna. Schwechat also had an aircraft factory that was bombed on June 26, 1944; and became a separate city in 1954.

B-24s bombed the Winterhafen oil depot. An underground storage installation was just west of Mainz, Mainz targets were also bombed by 22 B-17s on September 13, 171 B-17s on September 27, and the 466th on February 1 & 27, 1945. Mainz was captured on March 21. :2065
38 B-24s of the 450 BG targeted the Apollo oil refinery.
The 461 BG bombed the "oil storage installations" and earned a commendation from the 49th Bomb Wing commander (Lee).
With most of the effort on railways, four Mosquitoes targeted the Scholven/Buer oil plant
Mission 421: 88 B-17s bombed the Hanover-Misburg oil refinery.
The 485 BG bombed the oil installations at Giurgiu.

The 485 BG bombed the oil refinery. The Frontignan refinery was at Sète, and other small French refineries were at Gonfreville, Port Jerome, Martiques, Petit-Couronne, Etang de Berre, Dunkirk, L'Avere, Bec d'Ambes, Courchalettes, Gravenchon, 2 plants at Donges, and a shale oil refinery was at Autun.
The 464 BG bombed oil refineries at "Balaruc". A Balaruc-le-Vieux target was bombed on the 25th.
Mission 425: 169 B-24s bombed the Deurag-Nerag crude oil refinery. :217

Mission 425: B-17s bombed oil refineries at Hamburg/Deut.Petr.AG (53), Harburg/Ebano (60),Hamburg/Eurotank (107), Hamburg/Rhenania-Ossag (50), Harburg/Rhenania (53), Hamburg/Schliemanns (54), and Hamburg/Schindler (26).
123 Lancasters and 9 Mosquitoes attacked the synthetic-oil plant through cloud using Oboe skymarking and caused a loss of 20% production.
Mission 432: 101 B-24s hit an oil dump at Paris.
Mission 432: 33 B-17s hit the Rouen oil depot.
The 32 BS bombed a Ploieşti oil refinery.
Mission 438: 213 B-17s bombed Bremen oil industry. The 92 BG bombed the Bremen "oil storage complex".
Mission 441: 64 B-17s hit the Montbartier oil depot.
The 32 BS bombed Sète oil storage.
The Floridsdorf oil refinery and marshalling yard were bombed.
The 461 BG bombed "a refinery in the open country near the small town of Korneuburg".
The Lobau oil refinery was bombed.
The Schwechat aircraft factory and oil refinery were bombed.
The 464 BG bombed the Blechhammer South synthetic oil plant.
B-24s bombed oil industry. The Drohobycz (Nafta) refinery produced 35,000 tons/year.
Mission 445: 18 B-17s hit the Dugny oil depot.
Mission 447: 81 B-17s bombed the Böhlen synthetic oil plant.
The 461 BG & 464 BG bombed the South plant, and the 32 BS bombed the North plant.

"Our aviation gasoline production was badly hit in May and June. The enemy has succeeded in increasing our losses of aviation gasoline up to 90 percent by June 22. Only through speedy recovery of damaged plants has it been possible to regain partly … however, aviation gasoline production is completely insufficient … If we cannot manage to protect our hydrogenation factories and our refineries by all possible means, it will be impossible to get them back into working order from the state they are in now. If that happens, then by September we shall no longer be capable of covering the Wehrmacht's most urgent needs. In other words, from then on there will be a gap which will be impossible to fill and which will bring in its train inevitable tragic consequences." (Speer to Hitler) :1479
[456th_Bombardment_Group|456 BG bombed the "previously-untouched" Shell Oil refinery]
The 464 BG bombed the Shell oil depot at Belgrade.
The 32 BS bombed the Photogen oil refinery (formerly the Petroleum Refinery Transylvania).
The 464 BG bombed the oil storage at Porto Marghera.
The 461st BG bombed Ploieşti oil targets.
The Joint Oil Targets Committee was set up. :149
365 bombers attacked the North and South plants.
64 B-17s, out of a 303-bomber force of Flying Fortresses hit the Böhlen oil plant.
The 447 BG bombed Merseburg, and Leuna was shut down for 2 days. By July 19 production had risen to 53% of capacity.
102 B-24s, out of a 373-bomber force of Liberators hit the Lützkendorf oil plant.
The 464 BG bombed the oil storage at Porto Marghera.
The 32 BS bombed a Budapest oil refinery
26 B-24s of the 450 BG targeted the Ferencvaros marshalling yard and hit buildings, a factory, and a refinery.
The 32 BS bombed a Vienna oil refinery.
Aviation fuel production was 2,307 daily tonnes (40% of original production). :416
The 447 BG bombed Kiel oil targets. During the September 12 major assault on the German oil industry (Mission 626), 58 B-24s also bombed a Kiel target.
157 bombers attacked. The raid "achieved complete surprise through radio silence"
188 heavy bombers. The bombing destroyed 20% of the installations.
The 447 BG bombed the Merseburg "synthetic oil refinery".
166 bombers attacked the Ruhröl AG synthetic oil plant.
147 Lancasters attacked and caused severe damage
The 464 BG bombed the Româno-Americană refinery.
14 B-24s of the 450 BG targeted the "Kucove Oil Refinery" and previous bombing obscured the aiming point (there were "near misses" on the "old refinery").
119 aircraft attacked an oil refinery and storage depot at the start of a new campaign "against oil targets in the occupied Countries."
135 bombers attacked the Krupp GmbH synthetic oil plant.
The 464 BG bombed the Româno-Americană refinery and the 485 BG bombed the "Standard Oil Refinery" (B-24 44-40497 was abandoned after flying into the fireball of 41-29275).
The 461 BG bombed the Ploieşti Xenia oil refinery.
50 B-17s bombed the Bremen-Oslebshausen oil refinery.
The Bec-d'Ambes refinery that had opened at the Garonne/Dordogne river junction in 1931 was bombed.
The Pauillac oil store was bombed in clear conditions without encountering German fighters.
Mission 524: 74 B-17s bombed Genshagen, 45 hit Berlin diesel factories.
The 464 BG bombed a refinery at Le Pontet.
Le Pouzin oil storage bombed in SE France.
Lyon oil storage bombed in SE France.
The 464 BG bombed the Blechhammer North synthetic oil plant, and the 461 BG bombed the South plant.
The 384 BG bombed the Dungy oil depot.
353 bombers attacked the synthetic oil refineries at Blechhammer South (B-17s) and North (B-24s).
The 398th BG bombed the Dollberg oil plant. Also known as Dollbergen, the village near Hanover had an oil refinery.
The No. 205 Group RAF bombed the Româno-Americană refinery. The 205 Group also bombed Ploieşti on August 17. :239
B-17s bomb an oil refinery at Brod, Yugoslavia.
B-24s bomb an oil refinery at Budapest, Hungary. The 461 BG bombed the Almásfüzitő Oil Refinery.
The La Pallice refinery 30 miles from Bordeaux was destroyed.
450+ B-17s and B-24s bombed 6 oil refineries. The 464 BG bombed the Astra Română refinery, and the 461 BG bombed the Xenia oil refinery.
The 485 BG bombed the "Ober[raderach] chemical works".
The Rositz oil refinery was bombed.
The 92 BG attacked the Böhlen oil refinery in Leipzig.
The 487 BG bombed the Rositz oil refinery.
The 487 BG bombed the Zeitz oil refinery.
234 bombers attacked the synthetic oil plant.

65 B-17s with 125 P-51s escorts bombed 2 Ploieşti area oil refineries. Ploieşti was captured August 30 :204 after a total of 350 bombers had been lost attacking the area. :172 The Fifteenth Air Force had dropped 12,804 tons of explosives on Ploieşti targets, On October 17, a Fifteenth Air Force B-17 carried a photo crew to Ploieşti.
The oil refinery at Dubová was bombed.
B-24s bombed the oil refinery at Blechhammer.
B-24s bombed the Lobau oil refinery. The 461 BG bombed the underground oil storage at the refinery.
The Vösendorf oil refinery was bombed in the southern industrial area of Vienna.
The 485 BG bombed the Pardubice oil refinery.
Mission 568: 65 B-17s bombed Freital oil industry. This mission to Freital and Dresden was the 486 BG's longest mission. Dresden had a "Dresden Reick A.G." grinding wheel plant.
Mission 568: 88 B-24s bombed the Misburg oil refinery.
Three oil refineries were bombed at Kolín.
Mission 576: 73 B-24s bombed the Dülmen fuel dump.
Mission 576: 36 B-24s bomb the Emmerich oil refinery.
Mission 576: 89 B-17s bombed the Gelsenkirchen/Buer oil refinery.
The RAF re-started daylight bombing of Germany with an attack on the Homberg Fischer-Tropsch plant. :149
The 464 and 485 BGs bombed the Blechhammer South synthetic oil plant (the 485th commander became a POW).
B-17s hit Moosbierbaum oil refinery and adjacent chemical works.
The 464 and 485 BGs bombed the oil refinery.
Mission 605: 277 of 303 B-17s bombed the Ludwigshafen synthetic oil plant.
Mission 611: 348 of 384 B-17s attacked the Ludwigshafen/Opau oil refinery.
Mission 611: 166 B-17s bombed an oil depot at Kassel.
344 B-17s and B-24s bombed 5 ordnance depots and the SE industrial area in Vienna and 2 oil refineries in the area.
The 32 BS bombed the Schwechat oil refinery.
The synthetic oil plant was bombed.
The Dortmund synthetic oil plant was bombed.

Mission 623: At Fulda, 66 B-17s bombed the tire plant and 40 bombed the marshalling yard. Fulda also was the location of Gebauer & Moller ball bearing plant, and on September 12 (Mission 626), 46 B-17s bombed a Fulda target.

The Scholven/Buer synthetic oil plant was bombed. The RAF bombed a Gelsenkirchen target on September 29/30, as did the 466th on September 12 & 13, November 6 (the 466th bombed a Münster target on September 12 and March 25, 1945).
Mission 623: 87 B-24s bombed the oil refinery at Misburg and 88 bombed an engine factory at Hanover.
The synthetic oil plant at Kamen was bombed.
Mission 623: 75 B-17s bombed the Böhlen oil refinery. Böhlen was also bombed on August 15 (Mission 556), and the 384 BG bombed "Böhlen/Leipzig" on March 19, 1945.
Mission 623: At Magdeburg, 33 B-24s bombed the oil refinery and 27 bombed an ordnance depot.
Mission 623: 22 B-17s bombed the Ruhland oil refinery.
Wanne-Eickel synthetic oil plant bombed. A Wanne-Eickel target was also attacked by the 466th on July 25 and by US Forces in November 1944.
The Hoesch-Benzin GmbH synthetic oil plant at Dortmund was bombed.
The synthetic oil plant was bombed.
The synthetic oil plant was bombed.

Mission 626 dispatched 888 bombers and 662 fighters to 6 oil targets, including 34 B-24s that bombed Misburg oil industry. Misburg bomb damage from the September 11 & 12 attacks was repaired by October 15.
Mission 626: 35 B-17s bombed a Böhlen oil industry target.
Mission 626: 73 B-17s bombed a Magdeburg/Friedrichstadt oil target.
Mission 626: 59 B-17s bombed the Ruhland oil refinery.
Mission 626: 79 B-17s bombed the oil refinery at Brux.
The synthetic oil plant was bombed.
Mission 628: 74 B-17s bombed the oil refinery.
B-24s bombed the oil refinery at Odertal. An Odertal target was also bombed in bad weather on October 16.

Mission 628: 109 B-17s bombed the oil refinery at Stuttgart/Sindelfingen. Sindelfingen also had a Daimler Benz truck plant, and an aircraft engine factory at Sindelfingen was bombed on September 10, 1944.
The 464 BG bombed the Auschwitz synthetic oil and rubber plant.

"…the enemy always… after the resumption of work, …destroy[s] these [synthetic oil] installations again by air attack" (Speer). On July 20, Speer met with Ambassador Clodius of the Foreign Office regarding the "safeguarding of Rumanian oil." September "chemical plant" production was 5.5% of former capacity.

440+ B-17s and B-24s, with fighter escort, attacked 2 oil refineries and 4 marshalling yards in the Budapest area. The 464 BG bombed the Shell oil refinery at Budapest and the 485 BG bombed the "Magyar Oil Refinery".

In Czechoslovakia, the Bratislava "oil district" was bombed. Bratislava was the site of the Apollo refinery. The Bratislava "industrial area" was bombed on May 16, 1944, the "marshalling yards" were bombed on October 14, 1944, and "the town" of Bratislava was bombed on February 7, 1945.
147 B-17s, escorted by 290 P-38s and P-51s, bombed the Brüx synthetic oil refinery and the marshalling yard at Wels. Wels also had an aircraft facility.:40
Mission 652: 23 B-17s bombed the Magdeburg/Rothensee oil refinery.
Mission 652: 301 of 342 dispatched B-17s bombed the "Merseburg/Leuna oil refinery".
24 of 139 bombers attempted to hit the cloud-covered oil plant
Mission 662: 87 B-17s were dispatched to bomb the Wesseling oil refinery.

data: While clearing their personal belongings out of the club room, the girls find an old guitar that used to belong to Sawako. Since it had aged a bit, Sawako allows the girls to sell it and add the money to the club's budget. After visiting a home superstore to buy a storage shelf, they take the guitar to the music store where they are surprised to find it valued at ¥500,000. When Sawako inquires about the sale, Ritsu tries lying about its value, but it backfires when Sawako asks for a receipt and the club end up getting considerably less money. However, she allows the girls to buy one thing with the money. Noticing that Azusa looks a bit concerned about not having any freshmen to look after, the girls decide to get her a pet turtle, naming it Ton.

The light music club seniors go on a school field trip to Kyoto. On the train there, Mio is a little annoyed at Yui and Ritsu's childish behavior. Mio realizes that she will have to watch over both of them during the trip. After visiting various shrines and attractions, the group returns to the inn where the bad habits of the girls continue to annoy Mio as well as Sawako. The next day, they have a look around Kyoto, though Mio laments that no one wants to participate in any tourist activities. However, when they get lost on the way back to the train station along with Nodoka's group, Mio gives in to the jokey nature of the others and loosens up for the rest of the trip.

Azusa, along with her classmates Ui and Jun, spend time together while the light music club seniors are on their trip to Kyoto. Noticing that Ui would be lonely without her sister around, Azusa and Jun decide to sleepover at her house, in exchange for Azusa helping out with her underclassmen in the jazz club. After spending the night, they wake up to a rainy day. They go to an arcade where Ui hits a home run in a batting game, before Azusa is reminded that she needs to feed Ton.
